<div id="review_149580996" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/149580996" />
    <a title="Matthew" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/350406-matthew"><img alt="Matthew" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1572536199p2/350406.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/149580996?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew" href="/user/show/350406-matthew">Matthew</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/350406-matthew?shelf=gave-up">gave-up</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer149580996" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11236230724639630047">No matter how hard I tried, I just couldn&apos;t keep with this book. <br/><br/>The first part of the book discusses the manner in which officials from Los Angeles hijack the water from the Owens Valley in order to line the pockets of several businessmen, while ostensibly securing water for the future of Los Angeles. It is a compelling story, but early on, you get the sense that Marc Reisner is writing with a pretty irritated tone. <br/><br/>That tone persists as Reisner details a series of dam constructions in each sub</span>
  <span id="freeText11236230724639630047" style="display:none">No matter how hard I tried, I just couldn't keep with this book. <br /><br />The first part of the book discusses the manner in which officials from Los Angeles hijack the water from the Owens Valley in order to line the pockets of several businessmen, while ostensibly securing water for the future of Los Angeles. It is a compelling story, but early on, you get the sense that Marc Reisner is writing with a pretty irritated tone. <br /><br />That tone persists as Reisner details a series of dam constructions in each subsequent chapter. It isn't that Reisner is wrong to be annoyed by the bad decisions and greed that dictated the management of waters throughout the west, it is that he gets in a rut with writing about it over and over. I can't help feeling that he is just unhappy with everyone involved.<br /><br />I see a lot of other glowing reviews about this book, so perhaps I am missing something. However, when I compare this book to others about major public works projects (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2369.The_Great_Bridge_The_Epic_Story_of_the_Building_of_the_Brooklyn_Bridge" title="The Great Bridge The Epic Story of the Building of the Brooklyn Bridge by David McCullough" rel="nofollow noopener">The Great Bridge: The Epic Story of the Building of the Brooklyn Bridge</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2372.The_Path_Between_the_Seas" title="The Path Between the Seas by David McCullough" rel="nofollow noopener">The Path Between the Seas</a>), it just doesn't come close.<br /><br />I read about half this book and gave up.<br /><br />Recommended by Charles.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11236230724639630047" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

