<div id="review_2556594873" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2556594873" />
    <a title="Jason Young" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8467075-jason-young"><img alt="Jason Young" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1333257602p2/8467075.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2556594873?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jason Young" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jason Young" href="/user/show/8467075-jason-young">Jason Young</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/40803618-cadillac-desert">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8467075-jason-young?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8467075-jason-young?shelf=audio">audio</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8467075-jason-young?shelf=2018">2018</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2556594873" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1538110483144242832">One of the most horrifying, dystopic books I&apos;ve ever read. The asinine bureaucracy and cyclical destruction by way of solution of the early reclamation efforts is so incredibly frustrating and bizarre. The cowboy mind-frame and incessant growth that the American west felt entitled to gave rise to unforeseen, or disregarded, issues we&apos;re still dealing with, and will be for generations.<br/><br/>The afterword and postscript to the 2017 version do cast a light at the end of the tunnel. The efforts at the loc</span>
  <span id="freeText1538110483144242832" style="display:none">One of the most horrifying, dystopic books I've ever read. The asinine bureaucracy and cyclical destruction by way of solution of the early reclamation efforts is so incredibly frustrating and bizarre. The cowboy mind-frame and incessant growth that the American west felt entitled to gave rise to unforeseen, or disregarded, issues we're still dealing with, and will be for generations.<br /><br />The afterword and postscript to the 2017 version do cast a light at the end of the tunnel. The efforts at the local, state and federal level to disincentive waste, damming and over use seem to be going a long way, and household education has stemmed the tide of destruction. Lake Mead is still nearing all time lows and rivers are still dry, but the nightmare we were headed toward is at least approaching a little slower.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1538110483144242832" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


